<TEXT>
israels leftleaning labor party voted 
by an overwhelming majority thursday to reenter negotiations with 
the hardline likud bloc on forming a joint national unity 
government 
the decision was a reversal of the partys 110member executive 
bureau which last week voted against further talks 
it also was seen as a boost to the leadership of foreign minister 
shimon peres who pushed hard for a vote in favor of new 
negotiations 
if this were not the vote people would say it was a personal 
defeat so i suppose its a personal triumph peres told reporters 
after the results were announced 
the vote of the central committee was 637 to 348 just under 
1000 of the committees more than 1300 members attended the 
session in this tel aviv suburb 
both peres and the partys no 2 man defense minister yitzhak 
rabin made emotional pleas in favor of reopening talks with likud 
they pledged however that they would agree to join a coalition 
government only if it would advance the peace process and was 
committed to reforming the electoral system 
for 11 years the likud has been in power peres told the 
committee almost all that is dear to us has been affected what 
should we do be proud and go home or try to find a solution and 
change the system 
he added virtually screaming into the microphone i did not 
come to arrange negotiations but to examine our souls 
likud first came to power in 1977 and likud and labor have 
governed israel in an uneasy coalition since inconclusive elections 
in 1984 
israeli elections nov 1 again ended indecisively with likud 
winning 40 seats to labors 39 the remaining 41 seats were divided 
among smaller parties 
prime minister yitzhak shamir of likud has been asked to form a 
new government and needs the support of labor or several of the 
smaller parties to achieve a majority in the 120seat parliament or 
knesset 
intense bargaining has been going on since the election 
on thursday talks were held between likud leaders and the tehiya 
party a nationalist party with three seats in the new parliament 
and a tentative agreement was signed that would give a tehiya member 
the energy ministry portfolio israel television reported 
likud officials also met with three other small parties but no 
agreements were reached israel radio said 
</TEXT>
