<TEXT>
an attractive new production of aida at the 
metropolitan opera avoids the visual silliness of the two 
productions that arrived before it this one makes dramatic use of 
the stage elevator to change sets 
the opening night of the new aida a met opera guild benefit 
was tastefully conducted by james levine and gloriously sung by 
leona mitchell as aida placido domingo as radames fiorenza 
cossotto as amneris sherrill milnes as aidas father amonasro and 
paul plishka as the high priest 
domingo sounded sterling throughout he surprised this listener 
by taking the optional lower ending not the high c at the end of 
celeste aida 
miss mitchell singing her first aida at the met bloomed into 
full vocal glory in the third act she had longing in her voice in 
o patria mia and some beautiful pianissimos her voice has 
matured marvelously and still has youthful freshness 
in many operas the love music is in the first act before things 
start to go wrong in aida the love music is in act 4 after 
things have gone so wrong that aida and radames are sealed in a 
vault to die their duet was so beautiful that the audience didnt 
immediately break the spell with huge applause at the end of it 
miss cossotto who made her met debut as amneris in 1968 is a 
fine musician using her voice to brilliant advantage her stage 
personality while not flamboyant is striking placing amneris 
royal but hopeless love for radames in the foreground in the first 
two acts miss mitchells more retiring demeanor put aida in the 
background 
milnes was in brilliant voice and form amonasro may be a captive 
but hes full of vitality and vibrant with plans plishka sang with 
admirable authority 
the costumes by dada saligeri were mostly white trimmed with 
gold domingo began a hero in all gold and ended disgraced in a 
dark striped tunic 
some scenes were played near the front of the stage in front of 
a wall with huge bas reliefs of two seated egyptians then this 
would lift for a scene using more of the stage 
the most dramatic theatrical stroke is having amneris room in 
act 2 sink out of sight first soldiers are seen standing on top of 
the set thats descending then a platform for the king and amneris 
is revealed then all the citizenry now joined at ground level by 
the soldiers wait for the triumphal entry scene 
in the final scene the elevator is used again so the audience 
sees aida and radames in the vault and amneris in a temple above 
them 
there is no silly dance in act 1 while radames receives his armor 
and no fight to the death during the triumphal entry scene there is 
a dance there by choreographer rodney griffin of philadelphia 
making his met debut but it isnt silly 
gianni quaranta who is italian and won an academy award in 1987 
for art direction for a room with a view designed the sets 
sonja frisell a native of great britain who was on the staff of la 
scala for 15 years did stage direction 
both making met debuts proved to be stars of the show 
