<TEXT>
the us warplane that crashed into an 
apartment building in west germany killing four people has one of 
the best safety records in the air force inventory 
the a10 thunderbolt ii is an older model groundattack plane 
designed to be highly maneuverable at low speeds and low altitude 
and to carry a lot of bombs and ammunition 
the air force said the crash was the 14th serious socalled 
class a accident since oct 1 when the current fiscal year began 
although it was the first involving an a10 
at the same point in the last fiscal year the service had 
experienced nine class a accidents 
among the 14 accidents recorded since oct 1 have been two 
involving the new b1b bomber one involving a b52 bomber and one 
involving an f16 fighter in spain last monday that killed the 
general in charge of air force personnel in the mediterranean 
the air force says it is impossible to predict what type of 
safety record it will post for the year based on little more than 
one months passage during fiscal 1988 for example the service 
experienced a grim record for its f16 jet fighter and yet finished 
the year by posting one of its best overall safety records in 
history 
nonetheless it is true that our mishap rate has suddenly 
spiked up and we dont know why said one air force official who 
asked not to be identified 
we continue to examine our training procedures maintenance and 
everything else 
wednesdays crash involved an a10 on a training flight that 
inexplicably slammed into an apartment building in remscheid west 
germany killing at least four people injuring dozens of others and 
destroying homes for more than a block 
the a10 is designed to support soldiers on the ground by 
attacking enemy tanks and other highpriority targets the 
thunderbolt first flew in 1975 and became operational with the air 
force in 1977 the plane is no longer in production but the air 
force has more than 700 of them in its inventory 
statistically the a10 over time has been the safest fighter or 
attack plane currently in the inventory the aircraft has chalked up 
a major accident rate of less than 4 class a mishaps per 100000 
flying hours over its lifetime which now consists of more than 
175 million flight hours 
a class a mishap is one in which there is either a fatality or 
damage exceeding 500000 to an aircraft 
in the fiscal year ended sept 30 the air force lost three 
a10s for a mishap rate of 137 per 100000 flight hours by 
comparison the a7 had a mishap rate of 604 per 100000 flight 
hours the f16 a rate of 680 per 100000 flight hours and the 
b52 a rate of 204 per 100000 flight hours 
the overall air force rate for the last fiscal year was 163 
serious mishaps per 100000 flying hours representing 55 total 
accidents just slightly worse than the services alltime best of 
153 set in fiscal 1986 
the surge in air force accidents over the past month comes at a 
time when the other military services continue to report stable 
rates 
the navy for example which enjoyed its safest year ever in 
fiscal 1988 is on track toward an even safer year since oct 1 
the navy has experienced only four class a accidents it recorded 37 
in all of fiscal 1988 or more than three per month on average 
</TEXT>
