<TEXT>
demands for new peacekeeping missions could 
force the financially strapped united nations into insolvency in 
1989 according to a report by un secretarygeneral javier perez 
de cuellar 
the un chiefs pessimistic assessment was released thursday 
before he left for oslo norway to accept the 1988 nobel peace 
prize on behalf of un peacekeepers worldwide 
the nobel includes a cash prize worth about 390000 but that 
wont make much of a dent in the 4501 million in unpaid dues that 
un members owe the united states owes 3373 million 
un officials havent announced how the award money being 
collected saturday will be used 
on wednesday soviet president mikhail s gorbachev spoke to the 
general assembly and called for a new un peacekeeping force in 
afghanistan to oversee establishment of a broadbased government 
un officials already are drafting plans for a 7500member 
peacekeeping force to monitor southwest africas transition to 
independence plans also are under way to send 2000 peacekeeping 
troops to monitor an independence referendum in western sahara 
perez de cuellar predicted that in 1989 the united nations will 
collect 7793 million but will spend 8039 million ending the 
year with a loss of 246 million 
he based his projections on current payment patterns 
the united nations has yet to leave behind the spectre of the 
financial crisis throughout 1988 the organization has confronted 
the possibility of imminent bankruptcy which it has narrowly 
managed to avoid so far perez de cuellar wrote in the report 
only 79 of the 159 member states had paid all their dues as of 
nov 30 he said of the 80 member states still in arrears 40 
owed more than their 1988 assessments he added 
assuming next years payment patterns are like 1988 the un 
chief said the organization would manage to avoid insolvency but 
only by once again utilizing its reserves to meet cash requirements 
at many points during the year 
the united nations has a contingency reserve fund of about 210 
million that must be replenished as soon as new dues are paid the 
united nations often dips into this fund to start new peacekeeping 
operations or to meet operating costs 
the financial situation of the united nations could rapidly and 
dramatically deteriorate should any additional demands be placed 
upon these depleted reserves to meet the cash requirements for 
existing or new peacekeeping operations the report says 
president reagan said in september that the united states would 
gradually repay all its dues it has withheld money in recent years 
to protest what the reagan administration saw as mismanagement 
overstaffing and an antiwestern bias at the united nations 
