<TEXT>
an inspection prompted by last years fatal 
london subway fire found many weaknesses in fire safety precautions 
and emergency preparedness in new yorks subways 
eleven of the subway systems 48 escalators lack sprinklers 
about one quarter of the token booths inspected have inadequate 
emergency communications equipment and about half the fire 
extinguishers that are supposed to be along the tracks are missing 
or empty according to a report on the inspection released thursday 
the fire in the london underground which killed 31 people began 
when someone dropped a lighted match on a wooden escalator the new 
york subway system does not have wooden escalator treads 
after the london fire the new york city transit authority 
reactivated an old contract to install sprinklers at all 48 
escalators at a cost of 57 million but a month later called off 
the project because of budget concerns 
the new york subway system has not had a fire like the one at 
kings cross station in london but it averages 5000 blazes a year 
mostly minor car and track fires caused by rubbish 
larry reuter the transit authoritys vice president for rapid 
transit said that since the audit his agency has made safety 
improvements and plans more 
the audit found 11 of the subway systems escalators are not 
equipped with sprinklers and warned that inadequate cleaning allows 
flammable debris and grease to build up beneath them 
there have been three escalator fires in the past five years two 
in escalators without sprinklers both apparently were sparked by 
cigarettes although smoking is illegal in the subway system 
since the audit the transit authority has intensified its 
escalator maintenance reuter said 
the audit also found that of the 118 token booths checked 28 had 
neither a working emergency communication system nor a substitute 
auxiliary phone these systems are used to contact the transit 
authority command center which is responsible for calling the fire 
department 
reuter said an 118 million contract to replace the transit 
booth communications systems has been awarded 
transit authority president david gunn wrote in his response to 
the inspection that the authority is trying to deter thefts of fire 
extinguishers 
locking or otherwise securing extinguishers in the tunnels was 
deemed unacceptable he said police stakeouts also are 
utilized this situation is still being studied 
