the kentucky court of appeals today ordered 
the state board of claims to hold hearings on a group of claims 
filed against the state after the 1977 beverly hills supper club 
fire that killed 165 people 
the board had dismissed the claims without notice in 1987 saying 
it had the inherent power to do so and that it would not have 
been liable to the claimants anyway 
but the appeals court said in a precedentsetting opinion that 
the board and similar administrative agencies unlike courts have 
no inherent powers 
the board of claims is entirely a creature of the legislature 
there is no explicit grant of authority in kentucky law giving 
the board the power to take on an adversarial role and dismiss 
claims on its own motion the court said in a 21 ruling 
the board was created by the general assembly to handle damage 
claims against state agencies which under the kentucky constitution 
cannot be sued for negligence 
the fire on may 28 1977 led to years of litigation against 
dozens of companies that manufactured materials used in the 
