<TEXT>
on horseback and oxdrawn wagons 
afrikaners paraded into the city friday to celebrate the 150th 
anniversary of the white pioneers trek into the countrys heartland 
the march held seven days before the official anniversary was 
organized by rightwing white groups they object to the upcoming 
governmentbacked ceremony which has been billed as open to all 
races 
nearly 1000 whites dressed in 19th century pioneer outfits 
arrived in downtown pretoria to mark the great trek the 1838 
journey by afrikaners away from the britishruled cape colony into 
the countrys uncharted interior 
altogether about 3000 people attended the parade with wagons 
arriving from several locations across the country 
the great trek is the most momentous event in afrikaner history 
stories about hardships on the journey and battles with african 
tribesmen have taken on mythical proportions for the dutchdescended 
afrikaners who dominate the government 
today we remember how our ancestors built this country into a 
civilized area where its safe for whites to live said dann 
combrink 62 
combrink wearing a leather vest and widebrimmed hat was 
accompanied by his wife in a period costume that included a bonnet 
and a fulllength lavender and white dress with lace trim 
this a day afrikaners should be together said combrink 
organizers said blacks were not welcome at fridays ceremony or 
at an evening gathering at the voortrekker monument a huge granite 
structure on a hill overlooking the capital 
the great trek marked the coming of our oppression the 
stripping of our rights said a 45yearold black man who asked to 
be identified only as george when i see this i am very angry 
very bitter 
the 100th anniversary commemoration held in 1938 is regarded as 
the catalyst that united the afrikaners and gave impetus to their 
political organizations ten years later the afrikanerdominated 
national party came to power and began codifying their apartheid 
policies of racial segregation 
but the two separate trek celebrations illustrate the fracture 
between rightwing afrikaners who oppose all concessions to the 
countrys black majority and presidents pw bothas national 
party which calls for gradual race reforms and limited 
powersharing 
fridays ceremony was organized by the afrikaner peoples guard 
a rightwing cultural group the contingent that received the 
loudest applause was from the neonazi afrikaner resistance 
movement led by the charismatic eugene terreblanche 
most members of terreblanches group opted not for the 19th 
century attire of their ancestors but wore khaki outfits with 
swastikalike emblems on the shoulders 
terreblanche and his followers received sustained cheers as they 
rode around church square in the city center in front of the 
courthouse where five black antiapartheid leaders were sentenced to 
prison thursday on treason and terrorism convictions following a 
controversial trial 
the governmentsponsored trek left cape town on aug 27 for the 
870mile trip to pretoria despite the governments announced 
intention of opening the celebrations to all races few nonwhites 
have participated 
the government functions will dominate the next week leading up 
to the day of the vow a national holiday on dec 16 
on that day in 1838 the afrikaners vowed to make the date 
forever holy if they defeated a hostile zulu tribe they did so in 
the battle of blood river and the day remains the most revered in 
afrikaner history 
