<TEXT>
gas leaked past a caulked seal in the nozzle of 
a rocket booster used to launch space shuttle discovery in 
september but a nasa official said friday that this was anticipated 
by the design and is a nonproblem 
royce mitchell manager of the booster program at the marshall 
space flight center said in a telephone interview that an 
examination of the disassembled discovery solidfuel rockets showed 
the engines worked as expected and that the gas leakage has been 
seen in testing and is considered a normal event 
were very happy with these motors mitchell said 
mitchell said engineers examining the disassembled rocket parts 
found that gas seeped between panels of ablative material in the 
nozzle of one of the two boosters 
the national aeronautics and space administration official said 
the nozzles of the solid rocket boosters are lined with panels of 
ablative material that is designed to burn away during the firing of 
the rocket this action keeps extreme heat from penetrating the 
interior of the rocket nozzle 
between the panels of ablative material mitchell said engineers 
designed in a small gap to allow for thermal expansion 
as just one more little protection we inject an rtv room 
temperature vulcanizing silicone in there he said from time 
to time we get some gas past this thermal filler 
but he said the rocket booster nozzle is designed to accommodate 
this gas leakage and that the leak seen on the discovery rocket 
engines was not unexpected or damaging two oring seals are the 
primary protection against leak of the gas and neither of these 
seals showed that they had been touched by superheated gas or flame 
mitchell said that during fullscale tests of the rocket motor 
an unfilled 10inch gap was left between the ablative panels of the 
nozzle to demonstrate that were tolerant to a leak through that 
gap 
not even the sheen was taken off the surface of the o rings 
mitchell said of the test 
the accident that destroyed challenger which blew up 73 seconds 
after liftoff from the kennedy space center in january 1986 was 
blamed on the leak of gas or flame from a field joint of a solid 
rocket booster 
since then the rocket engines have been redesigned and tested 
with fullscale firings the discovery launch in september the 
first shuttle mission since challenger used the new rocket design 
mitchell said engineers are only now beginning to examine the 
engines used last week for the launch of space shuttle atlantis but 
that no problem has been found with those rockets 
this is a good motor he said were ready to fly again 
the next shuttle flight is scheduled for january 
