<TEXT>
a federal judge ruling in the nations first case 
challenging the constitutionality of the emergency housing 
preservation act upheld the law in an opinion favoring lowincome 
tenants in a gentrifying neighborhood 
although other courts do not have to follow its example the 
ruling could influence other challenges to the 1987 act which was 
designed to protect rentcontrolled federally subsidized private 
housing for low and moderateincome families an attorney for the 
plaintiffs said friday 
attorney daniel burke called thursdays ruling a victory for rent 
rights of the poor who are threatened by an increasing number of 
young professionals moving into renovated innercity neighborhoods 
us district judge james moran issued his ruling in a 
classaction lawsuit filed on behalf of 600 residents of a north 
side building 
the act prohibits private owners of federally subsidized housing 
from immediately charging higher market prices for rent if the 
change would result in a reduction of available low and 
moderateincome housing 
the case moran ruled on involved owners of a 209unit apartment 
building who sought to pay off a federally insured mortgage 20 years 
early 
the partnership that owns the building known as the 833 buena 
joint venture gave the us department of housing and urban 
development 18 million in january to pay off the mortgage and then 
sent eviction or rentincrease notices to the 600 residents 
believing the paidoff mortgage had exempted them from the 
regulations 
the owners maintained that the housing preservation law was 
unconstitutional and deprived them of their property without due 
process 
and in any event they said they paid up before the president 
signed the bill on feb 5 burke said 
but moran noted that the law clearly had a retroactive effective 
date of nov 1 1987 and said hud had made a conscious choice to 
ignore a legislative demand in accepting the prepayment said 
william wilen another attorney for the plaintiffs 
morans ruling means the building will remain under hud 
regulatory control it means rent increase proposed in february were 
unlawful burke said 
the buildings owners did not return phone messages friday and 
their attorney ellen babbitt refused to discuss the case 
burke called the ruling an influential decision in that its 
the first decision of any court on the constitutionality of the 
act he said 
other courts are not bound by this judgment but we think it 
will affect their decisions on similar challenges to the law he 
said 
wilen said one similar case is pending in federal court in 
raleigh nc 
what the law provides is that an owner who wishes to prepay a 
federal mortgage has two options one is to prove to hud that the 
prepayment and resulting rent increases would not have a harmful 
effect for housing opportunities for lowincome people and 
minorities burke said 
under that option owners would have to demonstrate that 
theres a surplus of lowincome housing in their neighborhood 
he said 
if they cant establish that they can ask for additional 
financial incentives from hud such as an increase in subsidies 
that would still keep them under federal jurisdiction the attorney 
said 
the owners of the buena building did neither he said 
