<DOCNO> AP881209-0138 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
nato should be cautious about soviet proposals 
for deep reductions in european troop levels because krelim leaders 
believe they still could win a war with fewer soldiers than they 
have now a congressional study said friday 
the report by a trio of congressional agencies was completed 
before the announcement of troop reductions made wednesday by soviet 
president mikhail s gorbachev 
gorbachev in a united nations speech said the soviet union 
would reduce its military forces 10 percent worldwide that would 
include the withdrawal of some soviet troops and tanks from eastern 
europe 
fridays report was prepared by the general accounting office 
the office of technology assessment and the congressional research 
service it was done in response to last years pentagon budget 
bill which ordered a wideranging study of the military balance 
between the north atlantic treaty organization and the soviet union 
and its warsaw pact allies 
the study sounded four major warnings about the onging 
ussoviet efforts to negotiate lower levels of troops and military 
power in the european theater the cautionary notes were based on 
the possibility of a soviet attack on nato 
the study said 
first because the soviets do not believe that they must have 
superiority across the theater in order to achieve victory caution 
must be exhibited in any agreement for force reductions 
it noted the soviets now enjoy at least a 2to1 advantage in 
many major measures of military might but it noted that soviet 
writings suggest that the soviets could have a force advantage 
across the theater of as little as 125 to 1 or even parity and 
still achieve victory 
any overall symmetrical reduction in forces would not be to 
natos advantage given that lowering the density of forces by 
soviet calculations would aid the attacker and make rapid advance 
and maneuvers easier 
unless all equipment is disabled or destroyed the soviets 
could agree to force reductions knowing that a dramatically reduced 
division would be capable of regneration in a few weeks 
finally nato should not expect any significant unilateral 
reductions on the part of the soviets either to promote good will 
or to pressure nato into an equivalent response that would not 
also be in the soviet unions own military and political interests 
the report studied soviet military attitudes toward the west and 
concluded that soviet planners believe that they have a marginal 
advantage in the conventional balance in europe today although they 
are far less optimistic about the future 
the soviets dont believe they need a numerical advantage to win 
a military attack the study said instead the ability to mass at 
decisive places and times with sufficient forces to achieve their 
objectives is the key 
while the soviets have roughly a 2to1 manpower advantage now 
the soviets apparently have concluded that a 15to1 force 
advantage or even parity across the entire theater may be 
sufficient to enable their forces to achieve a 3 or 4to1 force 
advantage on a few breakthrough sectors and 4 to 8to1 advantage 
at the tactical point of penetration the study said 
the study was prepared by a variety of experts including 
comptroller general charles bowsher head of the gao former arms 
negotiator jonathan dean rep charles bennett dfla chairman of 
the house armed services seapower subcommittee lawrence korb 
former assistant secretary of defense and james woolsey former 
undersecretary of the navy 
the report offered no clear answer to the question of who is 
ahead nato or the warsaw pact it noted that neither side has 
such an overwhelming advantage that its victory would be assured 
but it added that most scenarios favor the warsaw pact as the 
victor rather than nato nato has a chance of success but it needs 
to address its many shortcomings to enhance that chance 
the study said despite problems in measuring the nato and 
warsaw pact force balance the experts agreed that natos peacetime 
deterrent position is good and that its conventional capabilities 
have improved over the last decade but they should be better 
if the soviets struck quickly nato likely could do a good job of 
defending the west the study said but in a long fight the balance 
might swing toward the warsaw pact because of nato shortcomings in 
logistics and stockpiles of weapons and ammunition 
</TEXT>
