<TEXT>
sowetos new city council will stop 
evicting residents of the black township who have taken part in a 
3yearold rent boycott and will not force them to pay back rent 
antiapartheid activists said friday 
the delegation of activists made the announcement after meeting 
with the black council for several hours the delegation included 
anglican archbishop desmond tutu miners union leader cyril 
ramaphosa and others who in the past have refused to negotiate with 
the council 
the rent boycott is one of the most effective forms of protest 
still available to blacks under the 30monthold state of emergency 
the boycott was launched in 1985 to press a broad range of 
grievances against the government overdue rent in soweto alone is 
believed to exceed 100 million 
authorities have used numerous tactics to try to break the 
boycott including latenight eviction raids such as one in august 
1986 which led to the deaths of nearly 30 blacks in a confrontation 
with police 
fridays meeting came two days after south africas highest 
court the appeal court in bloemfontein ruled that previous 
councils of the township had no legal authority to collect rent from 
occupants of the thousands of homes built in the 1940s and 1950s by 
the city council of neighboring johannesburg at the time there was 
no separate black administration in soweto 
the rev frank chikane secretarygeneral of the south african 
council of churches and leader of the activists delegation said 
the councilors agreed that because of the court ruling no sowetan 
was required to pay any of millions of dollars of rent withheld 
during the boycott 
chikane said further negotiations would take place to determine 
whether some residents should now be awarded ownership of their 
houses and what type of rent or service charges should be paid in 
the future 
he and tutu indicated activists viewed the new council more 
positively than its predecessors 
they are people who want to do good people who honestly 
believe they can change the system chikane said whether they 
can it subject to an apartheid parliament remains to be seen 
they told us our grievances were their grievances tutu said 
under south africas system of apartheid the nations 26million 
black majority has no say in national affairs black local councils 
have been denounced by activists as subordinate extensions of the 
whitedominated political system 
sowetos new council took office following nationwide municipal 
elections oct 26 which were the target of an illegal but successful 
boycott by blacks about 115 percent of the eligible voters in 
soweto cast ballots 
the new council seeking to distance itself from the old ones 
proceeded to rehire municipal workers fired during a strike and said 
it wanted to consult with community leaders to solve problems facing 
its 25 million residents 
one of the consequences of the fivemonth municipal workers 
strike was an accumulation of trash on roadsides throughout soweto 
the council is launching a cleanup campaign saturday and drew 
praise from the normally critical local newspaper the sowetan for 
a proposal to pay children to join the cleanup 
the activists said in a statement friday that negotiations with 
the council would continue only if it were able to guarantee that 
community leaders were not harassed or detained as they consulted 
with residents 
