<TEXT>
west germans on friday demanded 
curbs on nato military flights over this densely populated country 
to halt the toll from crashes that have killed 100 people this year 
several nato members including the united states temporarily 
suspended training flights after thursdays fiery crash of a us 
warplane that killed five people but there were calls for permanent 
cuts 
the governor of the state where the a10 thunderbolt ii crashed 
said he will take the issue to the federal parliament another 
governor urged chancellor helmut kohl to negotiate with nato allies 
on any given day in west germany the sky is filled with the 
screechings and rumbles of hundreds of jets and helicopters and 
massive opposition has been fueled by recent tragedies 
even before thursdays fatal crash in remscheid 12 major 
accidents of military aircraft had killed 95 people this year they 
included 70 who died from an air show crash in ramstein in august 
the resistance took on added urgency after the a10 plowed into 
remscheid a city of 130000 about 15 miles east of duesseldorf 
the pilot capt michael p foster 34 of seal beach calif 
and four people on the ground were killed and 50 others were 
injured two dozen homes were destroyed 
the exact cause of the crash was under investigation but west 
german air force gen horst jungkurth said the pilot may have 
become disoriented when he tried to climb in heavy cloud cover to 
get out of bad weather 
however the state prosecutor for north rhinewestphalia joerg 
bachmann said witnesses reported seeing one of the planes two 
engines on fire before it crashed 
capt ron hahn a spokesman for the us air force team that went 
to remscheid after the accident said pilot error is one of the 
conclusions they air force investigators could come to but there 
is no way to comment on the likely cause ahead of that 
meanwhile state interior minister herbert schnoor accused us 
military officials of hindering initial rescue operations 
it took hours before the fire department found out from the 
americans what was in the aircraft he told regional radio wdr 
at first there was concern that there could be radioactive 
material on board 
the jet designed to support ground forces and fight tanks was 
carrying 1000 rounds of 30mm training ammunition when it crashed 
us air force officials said one rescuer said ammunition 
periodically exploded after the initial crash hindering rescue 
operations 
us ambassador richard burt and west german defense minster 
rupert scholz visited the site friday burt denied the flight was a 
lowlevel mission saying the a10 was flying between 2500 feet and 
3300 feet before it began to descend 
in west german military parlance lowlevel flights range from 
250 to 500 feet above the ground and are restricted to seven rural 
areas in the country but the number of training accidents in recent 
years has aroused widespread concern in a country of 61 million 
people with an area smaller than texas 
oskar lafontaine the popular leftist governor of saarland 
state said on kohl a conservative christian democrat should start 
to work immediately for a ban on lowlevel training flights and mock 
air battles over inhabited areas 
i am calling for negotiations with the allies as well as a 
corresponding decision for the german military towards the goal of 
eliminating any danger to the populace lafontaine told reporters 
in the state capital of saarbruecken 
johannes rau the social democratic governor of north 
rhinewestphalia state where the accident occurred said he will go 
to parliament to seek a reduction of lowlevel flights over his 
state 
i hope that finally all lowlevel flights over densely 
populated areas will be banned not just until christmas but 
permanently rau told reporters 
bernd wilz a leading christian democrat in parliament said he 
and many of his party colleagues are demanding a 30percent 
reduction in lowlevel training missions 
seven nato nations including west germany fly a combined 70000 
lowlevel training flights in this country each year more than in 
any other nato land according to the defense ministry in bonn 
the west german defense ministry said it will bar training 
missions below 10700 feet until the end of the year and called on 
the nations allies to observe a similar moratorium 
defense ministry spokesman winfried dunkel told a news conference 
in bonn that the united states had agreed to the temporary 
suspension to be lifted in january 
