<TEXT>
the burger king near penn station lets homeless 
customers have it their way up to a point the welcome ends if 
owners think the restaurant is becoming a stopgap shelter for smelly 
transients 
sometimes its difficult to put people out because you know 
they have no place to go said night manager cecil murray but 
you cant have vagrants it scares the normal customers 
some come in for five or 10 minutes just to get warm and wont 
buy anything some end up sitting there with the same thing for an 
hour i ask them to leave i cant have my boss see the whole place 
full of vagrants he said 
a week ago a homeless alcoholic man was dragged from a fast food 
eatery in san francisco and deposited on the sidewalk after passing 
out over his meal he lay there five hours before anyone noticed he 
was dead homeless advocates decried the incident as a toocommon 
example of societys callousness 
the san francisco episode highlights the predicament of fastfood 
restaurants which have become beacons for the homeless they dont 
want to banish people to the streets but neither do they want their 
family atmosphere disrupted by shabby creatures sometimes lugging 
all their worldly possessions in shopping bags and carts 
some places deal with the problem by posting time limits the 
burger king on eighth avenue allows no customer to linger longer 
than 20 minutes 
its fast food we need the seating space said manager mike 
barnes but if someone passed out inside i would call an 
ambulance you just cant carry them out to the street especially 
if they had made a purchase 
other places make casebycase decisions 
if they smell and bother other customers we tell them to 
leave said jose choe who runs a mcdonalds on canal street in 
lower manhattan 
we dont set a limit on how much money or how much time they 
spend as long as nobody is offended said jose martinez manager 
of a mcdonalds near grand central station if someone in a suit 
and tie is being a real pain we would escort them out 
advocates say thousands of homeless seek refuge in subway cars 
train stations bus depots or burger joints 
there are parts of the country ive been in where the local 
dunkin donuts is an emergency shelter by default said robert 
hayes founder of the citys coalition for the homeless 
as night follows day a human being afflicted by a cold wind is 
going to look for refuge hayes said but nobody with a 
reasonable option is going to sleep in a mcdonalds if there were 
reasonable alternatives this problem would disappear 
an estimated 30000 to 45000 people stay in abandoned buildings 
or public places nightly in new york not counting the ones sleeping 
in shelters hayes said an october survey by the transit authority 
found 1404 homeless living in new york subways 
nationwide no accurate census exists but an estimated 3 million 
people are without homes according to the national coalition for 
the homeless based in washington dc it agrees that restaurants 
make lousy sleeping quarters 
these places are not designed to function as housing said 
maria foscarinis spokeswoman for the coalition 
but there is no place else to go 
