<TEXT>
mikhail gorbachevs peacemaking new york visit 
and the opening of a glitzy soviet trade show underscored the 
importance the kremlin leader attaches to developing business and 
commercial ties in the west 
but perhaps unknown to many westerners the communist superpower 
has long been dabbling in overseas ventures that range from currency 
speculation in london to fish canning in north america 
while gorbachev may reduce the soviet military as he pledged in 
a speech at the united nations experts on the soviet bloc said they 
believe his broader reforms likely will make the soviets much more 
aggressive in foreign investing exporting and competing for 
customers in an increasingly global economy 
theyre beginning to talk about more direct investment abroad 
focused on firms that might help them market their own products 
said edward hewitt a soviet economics expert at the brookings 
institution a washington research organization i wouldnt be at 
all surprised if they come in and buy out some small european or 
us firms in the next few years 
the soviets have not acquired any significant western companies 
yet but the number of foreign firms owned wholly or partly by the 
soviets has risen sharply from about a dozen in the early 1960s to 
more than 120 now said carl mcmillan a soviet expert at carleton 
university in ottawa 
mcmillan who has compiled a list of soviet blocowned companies 
in the west for the past 10 years said many of these ventures 
reflect a growing sophistication about investing abroad 
there are different ways in which they do it he said they 
have assets portfolios and direct investments theyre in a wide 
range of business areas banks insurance engineering shipping and 
commercial companies 
the soviet investment presence abroad remains minuscule by 
western standards however considering that just one us or 
japanese conglomerate might have 120 foreign subsidiaries still 
the soviets appear to be catching on 
as they participate in the world economy theyve found this is 
the way everybody else plays the game mcmillan said 
in scandinavia for example the soviets have established a chain 
of governmentowned service stations to sell one of their biggest 
exports petroleum 
on this side of the world the soviets have stakes in two north 
american fishing and fishprocessing concerns cansov marine 
products ltd in nova scotia and marine resources co international 
in seattle 
as one of the largest producers of agricultural machinery and 
