now said jan vanous a soviet expert at planecon a 
washingtonbased consulting and information concern that studies the 
centrally planned economies of the soviet bloc 
a few years ago for example soviet traders attempted to push 
down the value of the swiss franc by dumping 50 million worth of 
francs in 20 separate orders throughout europe assuming dealers 
would not be able to communicate fast enough about who was selling 
the soviets were wrong losing money and respect 
it really caused a lot of bad blood vanous said you do 
this to someone in the foreignexchange market and the next time 
they deal with you theyre extra careful 
some traders have privately accused the soviets of eavesdropping 
on international telephone lines for advance word on central bank 
coordination and intervention which often moves a currency sharply 
the moscow norodny bank for example is believed to have once 
made huge profits on marks it bought just before the mark soared in 
value after the west german bundesbank made a surprise policy shift 
that change resulted from a telephone conversation hours earlier 
between aides from the bundesbank and the federal reserve in 
washington and according to one widely circulated story the soviets 
learned about it through a wiretap 
on the other hand the soviets can show remarkable naivete about 
economic trends that hurt their currency holdings they were active 
buyers of dollars just before the currency tumbled because of a 
coordination agreement by the leading western democracies and the 
collapse of oil prices a few years ago 
generally they are savvy in the short run but they dont do 
too well in the long run said vanous they are miserable in 
making forecasts they dont have the trained people the 
information and keep making judgments based on their own behavior 
