<TEXT>
a former president of the new jersey bankers 
association has been accused of leaking highly secret federal 
reserve board interest rate figures to a nowbankrupt brokerage firm 
seeking a jump on the securities market 
an indictment returned here thursday charged robert a rough with 
insider trading while a member of the new york federal reserve bank 
part of the feds regional network from 1982 to 1984 
rough 49 of layton nj received 47000 in interestdeferred 
loans from the nowdefunct bevill bresler amp schulman investment 
firm in exchange for the information the indictment charged 
rough is accused of relaying the data by telephone from his 
executive suite at the national bank of sussex county and once from 
the new york feds boardroom just after a meeting prosecutors told 
a news conference 
bevill bresler made millions of dollars in government securities 
trades based on roughs advance word about decisions made by the 
national federal reserve board on the discount rate and on 
recommendations made by the new york fed about the discount rate 
the indictment said 
changes in the discount rate the interest charged by the fed on 
loans to banks can have a strong impact on financial markets 
roughs attorney michael himmel would not comment in detail but 
said mr rough is going to enter a plea of not guilty and 
vigorously contest the charges 
roughs home telephone number is unlisted and he could not be 
reached for comment he resigned earlier this year as president of 
the national bank of sussex in branchville nj 
the new york fed is one of 12 regional banks in the federal 
reserve system all of which make recommendations every two weeks on 
whether the discount rate should be changed the national federal 
reserve board has the final say in setting the rate 
word that discount rate information was leaked surfaced in april 
1987 during a trial stemming from the collapse of bevill bresler 
prompting the fed to tighten its rules on disclosing the discount 
rate 
the allegations came to light during the trial of gilbert c 
schulman bevill breslers president on charges stemming from the 
144 million collapse of the livingston njbased firm in april 
1985 three other principals who pleaded guilty in the firms 
collapse in exchange for their cooperation testified about roughs 
allegedly passing on the information 
schulman a longtime friend of roughs is serving an 8year 
sentence for securities violations 
schulman testified that rough approached him for the 47000 in 
loans to buy a chunk of stock in the national bank of sussex 
rough faces 29 years in prison if convicted on all counts said 
us attorney samuel a alito jr rough was charged with conspiracy 
to commit wire and securities fraud two counts of bank fraud one 
count each of wire fraud and securities fraud and two counts of 
making false statements to banks 
no arraignment date has been set 
alito said rough violated a position of great power trust and 
responsibility and hoped the case would serve as a warning to 
other wouldbe insidertraders of interest rate data 
he abused that office in a very shocking and outrageous 
manner he said 
fed officials have called the discount rate one of their most 
closely guarded secrets the rate is widely regarded as an indicator 
of the direction in which the fed is seeking to push interest rates 
which affect the prices of bonds 
federal authorities were told by bevill bresler principals of 
the allegations against rough during interviews shortly after the 
firms collapse 
after the fed learned of them it stopped telling regional 
federal reserves of its decision on the discount rate earlier in the 
day than when it was announced publicly said new york fed spokesman 
peter bakstansky 
the indictment took so long because of the complex process of 
examining bevill breslers brokerage operations alito said 
he said the case was the first insidertrading scheme involving 
the discount rate and the first against a sitting member of a 
federal reserve bank 
rough sat on the board as a representative of small banks in the 
regional feds district 
