<DOCNO> AP881209-0214 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
in the next few weeks the media will attempt to 
wrap up the economic year and one of their themes is likely to be 
that 1988 was the year when it didnt happen 
so much didnt happen that was expected to happen a secondary 
shock wave in the stock market and a recession for instance that 
it carries a message for 1989 
that message dont place too much faith in the seers because 
they really dont put all that faith in themselves many of the 
stock market doomsayers for example reversed themselves last 
summer and put their bets on stocks 
another school of economic sages based their forecast of 
recession on the assumption that an expansion that had already gone 
on for five years would have to stop for breath instead the 
expansion merely slowed and inhaled 
now one year later these seers are expressing the identical 
doubts they had in 1987 and for the very same reasons it is a 
nolose situation because a recession that doesnt come can be 
explained away as unexpectedly good news and eventually if not 
now they will be right theyll let you know about it 
interest rates rose but they didnt go through the roof prices 
didnt run away housing didnt collapse cars had a good year the 
jobless rate continued to fall contrary to many forecasts the 
trade and budget deficits narrowed too 
the fact that these dire forecasts didnt materialize doesnt 
mean it was a dull year it wasnt a dull year but the things that 
made it exciting and unusual had very little to do with the 
foresight of the seers 
do you recall any of them telling you that corporate takeovers 
would reach such a frantic pace did anyone even conceive of a 
company the size of rjr nabisco being auctioned off 
it is therefore wise in reviewing the forecasts to remember that 
much of it is a game when you win you get up on the roof and shout 
and demonstrate and when youre wrong you remain in your study and 
guard your quiet dignity 
nothing can stop the forecasts theyll be made if only for 
publicity purposes the future oddly is an attractive place 
largely because it is the great unknown 
though it is a dark mystery the future is where much of the 
investment community seeks to reside you make money by 
anticipating by getting in on things early by beating others by 
buying before the news gets around 
and so there will be forecasts stock market seers make them to 
impress customers scholars sometimes make them because of 
conviction or probably to sell books market letter writers make 
them because forecasts excite interest 
but evidence that very few people really can foresee the future 
at least with any tiny degree of consistency lies in the consensus 
forecast about which you will be reading plenty 
the consensus forecast is the median forecast it is the middle 
range between extremes the consensus is often right on the mark 
correctly estimating such items as inflation interest rates and 
gross national product 
and when the consensus is on the mark it means by definition 
that most of the forecasts it is made of are not on the mark 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

