<TEXT>
in the world of credit short is most 
definitely in fashion these days at least from an investors 
standpoint 
yields on some bills and notes particularly in the treasury 
market have nearly equaled or surpassed those on longer maturing 
bonds more so now than at any other time this year that makes it 
far more sensible to hold onto the shorter securities 
usually its the other way around longterm rates often are 
significantly higher to compensate investors for their increased 
risk 
for instance its more likely that someone will renege on a 
30year debt than on one lasting three months theres also 
increased risk of higher interest rates which depress a bonds 
price and higher inflation which reduce its real value 
but now the socalled yield curve which illustrates the 
difference between short and longterm interest rates appears to 
be changing normally in an upward or j position the curve 
which has been flat for most of the year looks close to inverting 
by midday friday the yield on the treasurys bellwether 30year 
bond stood at 896 percent lower than the yields of all other bonds 
and notes of lesser maturities the 20year bond was yielding 902 
percent the 10year 901 percent the fouryear 900 percent and 
the twoyear 899 percent 
treasury bill yields remained a bit lower however a quick 
measure of the curve is the relationship between the threemonth 
bill and the 30year bond by friday afternoon the long bond was 
079 percentage points higher than the bill the gap though was 
closing in on the oneyear bill which was yielding 890 percent 
when the yield curve is in a positive upward steep the long bond 
is usually between 1 to 2 percentage points higher in yield 
the yield curve theoretically should reflect the expectations of 
borrowers and investors one that ascends steeply indicates that the 
markets expect interest rates and inflation to rise it also 
portrays easy money 
the last time the curve inverted was around 1981 the stock 
market fell into a slump as a result and the nation headed into a 
recession 
market watchers arent sure what the current movement of rates 
means 
jay goldinger a principal at the beverly hills calif 
investment banking firm capital insight inc said he expects the 
yield curve to continue to invert but that the economy shouldnt 
suffer as a result 
what it the inversion really means is inflation expectations 
in this country continue to be reduced as the fed has done a good 
job of tightening credit goldinger said 
this is nothing unusual we have an inverted yield curve in 
england and in australia he explained the central banks of 
this world really pay attention in focusing in on inflation fears 
marshall b front an economist at the chicago investment firm 
stein roe amp farnham predicted that rates might be heading lower 
soon because the economy is showing signs of slowing down 
while shortterm rates certainly are attractive now not just in 
treasuries but in things like certificates of deposits or money 
market accounts front says hes gradually sinking his money into 
longermaturing securities 
our own guess is that were fairly close to a peak in 
shortterm rates we could see a decline in rates before the end of 
the first quarter front said 
if that happens then bond prices will head higher 
we dont think well have a repeat of the last few cycles where 
you had a sharply inverted yield curve front said 
</TEXT>
