<TEXT>
a bipartisan commission appointed to study ways 
to reduce the federal budget deficit friday canceled its next 
meeting after a judge barred the panel from closing the proceedings 
to the public 
the decision by us district judge joyce hens green prompted the 
national economic commission to cancel mondays meeting at which it 
was to review budget options and discuss which economic assumptions 
would be used to make recommendations for deficit reduction 
it is evident in this case that the public has the right to 
know the issues at discussion as they develop at the december 12 
meeting green ruled in granting a temporary restraining order 
barring a closed proceeding 
the meeting is canceled commission spokesman jim hildreth 
said following greens decision we were challenged and we will 
abide by the court where we will go from here we simply dont 
know 
the commission has no other scheduled meetings this month and had 
only discussed tentative dates for discussions in january hildreth 
said 
the judge ruled that news organizations that brought the case 
would likely ultimately be able to prove that closed meetings 
violate the federal advisory commission act and the sunshine act 
the commissions insistence on shielding the debate as to 
budget options from public scrutiny directly contravenes the law 
green wrote in an opinion 
it chops the core of our democratic society open robust 
unvarnished public debate illuminating pressing issues concerns and 
policies that affect the lives of all citizens she said 
the judge rejected the commissions arguments that because the 
panels members were so prestigious their public discussions of 
various economic options could wreak havoc with the financial 
markets 
the expressions to be presented by these officials are no 
different than the plethora of economic assessments and predictions 
some optimistic some grave that inundate the public daily 
green said 
while such discussion may result in speculation on financial 
markets the effect must be balanced against the open society and 
unfettered public debate on important national issues upon which our 
democracy is founded the judge said 
a closed meeting would more likely encourage speculation he 
said adding fear flourishes when the process is shrouded in a 
cloak of secrecy and the swiftest transport to speculation is fear 
the lawsuit challenging the closed meeting was filed by the 
washington post the wall street journal the bureau of national 
affairs which publishes financial newsletters and stephen 
wildstrom an editor for business week 
public citizen a consumer organization founded by ralph nader 
represented the news organizations and also joined in the case 
in a statement public citizens president joan claybrook said 
the idea that the members of this commission are too prestigious 
to air their views in public is outrageous and an affront to our 
open system of government 
