<DOCNO> AP881209-0228 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
wall streets latest financial product the 
unbundled stock unit is being touted as a way for topquality 
companies to unlock the hidden values in their shares without having 
to dismantle the company 
but the proposal has also unleashed a torrent of questions from 
investors and money managers trying to figure if there is anything 
in it for them 
shearson lehman hutton inc which developed the proposal 
embraced by four major companies earlier this week has created a 
product that splits a stock into three components a 30year bond 
a preferred stock and a stock appreciation certificate 
american express co sara lee corp dow chemical co and pfizer 
inc have filed documents with the securities and exchange 
commission to offer their shareholders a chance to swap up to 56 
billion in stock for new securities 
while the sec reviews the filings money managers are trying to 
figure how the new securities will work what they will be worth and 
whether there will be be enough of them that there will be a ready 
buyer when a holder wants to sell 
while their inventors say they were not intended as a takeover 
defense some investors say they may have that effect critics say 
the tax savings for issuers inherent in the plans may invite 
congressional scrutiny 
jim rogers a professional investor and professor of finance at 
columbia universitys graduate school of business said the new 
securities are a waste of time i dont see whats in it for 
most people 
the question you have to ask yourself is do we really need 
another piece of paper to maintain our capital system said david 
dreman director of a money management firm that bears his name 
but ron gallatin the shearson executive who oversaw the 
invention of unbundled stock units said they will be useful for 
major companies with credit ratings strong enough to absorb some 
modest increases in debt 
he said they are designed to highlight the three reasons people 
buy stock the chance for a price increase the dividend and the 
possibility that the dividend will be raised 
the 30year bond will pay interest equal to the current annual 
dividend the preferred stock would pay any increase over the next 
30 years in the current level of the dividend the stock 
appreciation certificate would entitle the holder to buy a share of 
the companys stock in 30 years for a preset price expected to be 
slightly higher than the face value of the bond 
investors making the swap would be protected against a dividend 
reduction since the dividend would become a fixed interest payment 
but some investment managers wonder how liquid the market for the 
new securities will be 
youll only be able to determine that when they come out 
said charles minter a partner in the investment advisory firm 
comstock partners 
gallatin conceded that since the exchange of stock for an 
unbundled unit would be taxable the units should appeal mainly to 
taxexempt institutions such as pension funds 
those making the exchange would also give up their voting rights 
a development that some analysts suspect management would like 
if you remove 20 percent of the stock from the market you 
could end up with a higher percentage in friendly hands said 
kenneth heebner a portfolio manager at loomis sayles amp co in 
boston 
from the issuers standpoint the security may be especially 
attractive to companies that feel undervalued have little debt and 
want to avoid the heavy borrowing that would be needed to buy back 
stock for cash 
this is particularly attractive at a time when many american 
managers see other companies succumbing to takeovers at prices far 
in excess of market values the publisher macmillan inc foodmaker 
kraft inc and food and tobacco giant rjr nabisco inc have all 
fallen prey in recent months to takeover offers at a huge premiums 
to their stock prices 
the swaps would have a mixed financial impact on an issuer 
however 
on the one hand the company loses the flexibility of being able 
to reduce its costs in bad times it can always cut a dividend but 
not interest payments but the company would save on taxes since 
interest payments are deductible while dividends are not 
this plays into the hands of those in congress who say debt has 
become a device for avoiding taxes said james ullman trustee of 
batterymarch financial management 
a staffer on the house ways and means committee speaking on 
condition that he not be identified by name said the panel has 
taken no position on whether to investigate the uses of the 
unbundled stock unit and said whether it does so may depend on how 
many companies use it 
the one clear winner in all this investment managers say will 
be the underwriters who get a fee for handling the exchanges and the 
brokers who will get commissions on executing trades involving all 
of the new products 
it is a reflection of the battered shape of wall street said 
batterymarchs ullman 
</TEXT>
