<TEXT>
bond prices ended mixed in slow trading friday 
reflecting what creditmarket strategists called uncertainty over 
the direction of interest rates 
the treasurys 30year bond rose about point or 125 per 
1000 in face amount and its yield eased to 895 percent from 896 
percent thursday 
one noteworthy development was a rise in rates on shortterm 
treasury notes to yield more than that of 30year bonds an unusual 
shift that last occurred prior to the 198182 recession but the 
significance of the socalled inverted yield curve remains unclear 
bond strategists said the market was influenced largely by 
confusion over whether or when the federal reserve will move to 
tighten credit conditions in order to preempt inflationary pressure 
and keep the dollar stable 
they said the confusion may be clarified somewhat next wednesday 
when the commerce department is scheduled to release the 
marketsensitive monthly trade deficit figures for october a large 
imbalance could hurt the dollars value and force the fed to raise 
interest rates 
in the secondary market for treasury bonds prices of shortterm 
governments fell point intermediate maturities fell point and 
longterm issues rose point the telerate inc financial 
information service reported 
the movement of a point equals a change of 10 in the price of a 
bond with a 1000 face value 
the shearson lehman daily treasury bond index which measures 
price movements on all outstanding treasury issues with maturities 
of a year or longer fell 145 to 113557 
in corporate trading industrials and utilities also fell 
moodys investment grade corporate bond index which measures price 
movements on 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years or 
longer lost 100 to 29510 
prices strengthened slightly in the taxexempt market the bond 
buyer index of 40 actively traded municipal bonds was up 732 point 
at 90 as of 3 pm est the average yield to maturity was 790 
percent down from 792 percent thursday 
yields on threemonth treasury bills fell to 814 percent as the 
discount fell 8 basis points to 788 percent yields on sixmonth 
bills rose to 867 percent as the discount rose 4 basis points to 
821 percent yields on oneyear bills rose to 892 percent as the 
discount rose 5 basis points to 828 percent 
a basis point is onehundredth of a percentage point the yield 
is the annualized return on an investment in a treasury bill the 
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face 
value which is paid at maturity 
the federal funds rate the interest on overnight loans between 
banks traded at 8 percent unchanged from late thursday 
</TEXT>
